      <td>
      <td>John
     
  <p>In this example, James can challenge Sal, Fred, or Bob. If James challenges and defeats Bob, the ladder will shift as shown. 
  <p>If a player has shown up during a meeting, they count as present even if they have gone home early.
  <p>Once a player is number one, they will be protected from non-adjacent challenges. First place can only be challenged by second place. Second place can only be challenged by third place and fourth place. Players in the top 3 will also play best of 5 sets. Third place can be challenged by fourth, fifth, or sixth place. These players can be skipped though if they are absent. If you are the highest ranking present player, congratulations! You get first.
  <p>If you have any questions, comments, or suggestions, please contact Theo Landegger.
  Good Luck and Happy Smashing!
  
  <h1>Questions I Have Been Asked:
  <p>Q. If this is going to be a "rolling" tournament, any interest in allowing matches to happen outside of the wednesday get-together?
  <p>A. I don't want to force people to meet up if they are challenged on a not club meeting day. If two people agree to get together and do it though, they can do that.
  
  <p>Q. Do people higher in the ladder have to accept challenges from below?
  <p>A. Yes.
  
  <p>Q. Can I challenge someone again that I beat earlier in the same day?
  <p>A. No.
  
  